<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-exp-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Exponential Functions, Definitions and Graphs</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize an exponential function and distinguish it from a polynomial / power function
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify if an exponential function is modelling exponential growth or exponential decay based on its graph and/or equation
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify fundamental characteristics of exponential functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compare and contrast characteristics of exponential functions with those of polynomial functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe transformations of exponential functions. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe how transformations of exponential functions change the properties and characteristics (such as the horizontal asymptote and end behaviours) of the transformed function.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Define the number <m>e</m> and the natural exponential function <m>y=e^x</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
   
  <assemblage><title>Where will this be used in calculus?</title>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Exponential functions are an important family of functions that are used throughout calculus to illustrate calculus related concepts and to practice computations. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        Exponential functions are solutions to many types of differential equations that model the rate of changing quantities such as population growth, the spread of infectious diseases, and the cooling of a liquid.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Exponential functions are used to model the growth of an investment due to compound interest.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <introduction>
    <p>    
In <xref ref="sec-exp-intro"/>, we reviewed some fundamental exponent laws and learned how to re-write mathematical expressions involving exponents. 
While this gives us a strong understanding of exponential calculations, we will now start looking at properties and characteristics of the exponential function, 
which is often used in mathematical models to describe rapid growth or decay. 
A defining characteristic of exponential functions is that they change at a rate that is directly proportional to the amount of the quantity that is currently present.   
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection><title>What is an Exponential Function?</title>
  <p> 
    An <term>exponential function</term><idx>Exponential function</idx> is any function in the form <m>f(x)=b^x,</m> where <m>b>0</m> and <m>b \neq 1</m>.
    Here, we call the parameter <m>b</m> the <term>base</term><idx>Base of an exponential function</idx> of the function, which determines the type of exponential relationship that is being modelled: 
    </p>

<aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Note that we are focusing on <m>f(x)=b^x</m> where either <m>b \gt 1</m>, or <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>.
      If <m>b=1</m> then <m>f(x) = b^x = 1^x = 1</m> which does not have graphs similar to those seen here. 
      (What is the graph of <m>f(x) = 1</m>?) 
    </p>
  </aside>

<figure><title>Exponential Growth</title>
  <caption>
    <alert>Exponential Growth.</alert> If <m>b \gt 1,</m> the function <m>f(x)=b^x</m> illustrates exponential <alert>growth</alert>, 
    which can be used to model quantities that increase rapidly over time. The graph above is an example of a graph of <m>f(x)=b^x</m> where <m>b\gt 1</m>.       
  </caption>
  <image source="images/exp1growth" width="70%">
  </image>
</figure>

<figure><title>Exponential Decay</title>
  <caption>
    <alert>Exponential Decay.</alert> If <m>0 \lt b \lt 1,</m> the function <m>f(x)=b^x</m> illustrates exponential <alert>decay</alert>, 
              which can be used to model quantities that shrink exponentially over time.
              The graph above is an example of a graph of <m>f(x)=b^x</m> where <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>.
  </caption>
  <image source="images/exp1decay" width="70%">
  </image>
</figure>

