  <exercise><title>Exponential graphs - FROM WEBWORK</title>
    <webwork source="Library/LoyolaChicago/Precalc/Chap3Sec3/Q07.pg" />
  </exercise>

<p>
Exponential functions have numerical bases with variable exponents. 
It is important to not confuse this with power functions, which are functions of the form <m>f(x)=x^n</m>. 
The following table compares and contrasts power functions from exponential functions:
</p>

<tabular halign="center">
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
      <cell>Power Function</cell>
      <cell>Exponential Function</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=x^2</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=2^x</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=4x^3-2x+1</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=5(1.3)^x-3</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y= \sqrt x </m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=\big(\sqrt{0.85}\big)^x</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

  <exercise><title>Which are exponential? - FROM WEBWORK</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      In this question, think of an exponential function as ONE exponential function which may have been transformed by adding, subtracting, multiplying, and/or dividing constants. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <webwork source="Library/FortLewis/Algebra/10-1-Exponential-Functions/MCH1-10-1-1thru4.pg" />
  </exercise>
  </subsection>

 <subsection><title>Euler's Number and The Natural Exponential Function</title>
  <p>
While exponential functions can have infinitely many bases, 
there is one special exponential function that we will deal with almost exclusively in our calculus classes: The Natural Exponential Function.
  </p>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Euler's Number <m>e</m> is named after Leonhard Euler<idx>Leonhard Euler</idx> (1707-1783). 
      He also introduced the notation <m>f(x)</m> for functions.
      Read more about the remarkable  <url href="https://euler.euclid.int/about-leonhard-euler/" visual="https://euler.euclid.int/about-leonhard-euler/">mathematian 
       Leonhard Euler here</url>.
    </p>
  </aside>

   <assemblage><title>The Natural Exponential Function</title>
     <p>
<term>The Natural Exponential Function</term><idx>Natural exponential function</idx><idx>Exponential function</idx> is an exponential function 
whose base is the special number denoted <m>e</m>, called <term>Euler's Number</term><idx>Euler's number</idx><idx>e</idx>,  
  which is an irrational constant given by <m>e \approx 2.7182818 \ldots</m>.
  </p>
</assemblage>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should know (memorize) a few things about the number <m>e</m>. 
      You are expected to know that <m>e</m> is irrational, and <m>e \approx 2.7</m>.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <p>
    <alert>Why the number <m>e</m>?</alert>
  </p>
  <p>
  The base <m>e</m> is important because with this base, the slope of the exponential function at <m>x=0</m> is exactly 1. 
  That might not sound important now, but this means that when differentiating (which we will do a lot in calculus!) 
  this means that the derivative of <m>f(x)=e^x</m> is simpler than the derivative of any other exponential function.
  </p>
  <p>
    Later (using calculus) it will be possible to prove that the number <m>e</m> (with the special slope as above) is also given by 
    <md>
      \lim_{n \to \infty} \left(1 + \frac{1}{n}\right)^n
    </md>
  </p>

<p>
The natural exponential function, <m>y=e^x</m>, can be approximated by <m>y=2.718^x</m>, which can be thought of as simply an exponential function that grows 
faster than <m>y=2^x</m> but not quite as fast as <m>y=3^x.</m> 
The graph of <m>y=e^x</m> is shown in the diagram below along with the graphs of <m>y=2^x</m> and <m>y=3^x</m>.
</p>

<figure><title>Exponential Function</title>
  <caption><alert>Exponential Function</alert>
 The graph of <m>y=e^x</m> is shown here, along with the graphs of <m>y=2^x</m> and <m>y=3^x</m>. 
 Notice that all three functions intersect the <m>y</m>-axis at the same value, <m>y=1</m>.
  </caption>
  <image source="images/exp2" width="70%">
  </image>
</figure>

<p>
As we can see, <m>y=e^x</m> is characteristically similar to any other exponential function, and should not be thought of as a fundamentally "different" function. 
  For our purposes, we should think of the natural exponential function as simply being an exponential function with a specific base, <m>e</m>. 
</p>


<exercise><title>The Natural Exponential Function - HOMEMADE</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");
      $a = random(3,6,1);
      $ans = Compute("$a*x^($a-1)");
      $radio = RadioButtons([
          'It is the largest exponential function.',
          'It is the smallest exponential function.',
          'Its slope at x=0 is exactly 1.',
          'Its derivative is 0.',
        ],2);
        $popup1 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
        $popup2 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
        $popup3 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],2);
        $popup4 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);

      Context()->functions->disable('All');
      Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            What is special about the function <m>y=e^x</m> compared to other exponential functions?
          </p>
          <p>
                <var name="$radio" form="buttons"/>
          </p>
        </li>
          <li>
          <p>
            Are the following statements true or false?
          </p>
          <p>
                <m>y=e^x</m> is an example of an exponential function. <var name="$popup1" form="popup"/>
          </p>
            <p>
                <m>2 \lt e \lt 3</m>  <var name="$popup2" form="popup"/>
          </p>
          <p>
                The graph of <m>y=e^x</m> looks very different from graphs of other exponential functions. <var name="$popup3" form="popup"/>
          </p>
          <p>
                <m>y=e^x</m> is an important exponential function because it is easy to differentiate. <var name="$popup4" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      

    </statement>

  </webwork>
</exercise>
  </subsection>

 <subsection><title>Graphs of Exponential Functions</title>
<p>
Just like any other type of parent function, exponential functions have a set of "default" characteristics. 
Some of these characteristics may change based on the transformations of the function, but the standard exponential function <m>f(x)=e^x</m> has the following characteristics:
</p>

<tabular halign="center">
    <row>
      <cell>Domain:</cell>
      <cell><m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Range:</cell>
      <cell><m>y \gt 0</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Horizontal asymptote:</cell>
      <cell><m>y=0</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Vertical asymptote:</cell>
      <cell>None</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>x</m>-intercept:</cell>
      <cell>None</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y</m>-intercept:</cell>
      <cell><m>(0,1)</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

<figure><title>Exponential Function</title>
  <caption>
    The graph here is an example of a graph of <m>f(x)=b^x</m> where <m>b\gt 1</m>. This graph has the characteristics listed above.       
  </caption>
  <image source="images/exp1growth" width="70%">
  </image>
</figure>

<exercise><title>Function characteristics - HOMEMADE</title>
    <introduction>
      <image source="images/exp4" width="70%">
  </image>
    </introduction>

  <webwork>
      <pg-code>
        Context("Numeric");
        $f = Formula("sqrt(x)");
        Context("Interval");
        $domain = Interval("(-inf,inf)");
        Context("Interval");
        $range = Interval("(-2,inf)");
        Context("Point");
        $intercept = Point("(0,-1)");
        Context("LimitedNumeric");
        $ha = Real(-2);
      </pg-code>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The graph of an exponential function is given above. Answer the following questions about that graph. 
          <ol>
             <li>
              <p>
                What is the domain of the function, in interval notation? <var name="$domain" width="10"/>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the range of the function, in interval notation? <var name="$range" width="10"/>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the <m>y</m>-intercept of the function? <var name="$intercept" width="10"/>. (Enter your answer in point form, for example <m>(3,5)</m>.)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the equation of the horizontal asymptote? The horizontal asymptote is <m>y=</m> <var name="$ha" width="10"/>. (Enter a single number.)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </webwork>
</exercise>


<p>
As you may have seen in your previous sudies, any parent function, <m>y=f(x)</m> can be transformed using the following parameters:
<md>y=af[k(x-d)]+c</md>
</p>
<p>
Applying these parameters to the natural exponential function, we obtain the general equation for a transformed exponential function:
<md>y=ae^{k(x-d)}+c</md>
</p>
<p>
We will focus mostly on the cases where <m>d=0</m>. 
</p>

